AVIAN INFLUENZA (238): CHINA (HONG KONG) WILD BIRD, HPAI H5N1, WOAH
*******************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Thu 15 Dec 2022
Source: WOAH-WAHIS (World Animal Health Information System) 2022 [edited]
https://wahis.woah.org/#/in-review/4778


Hong Kong - Influenza A viruses of high pathogenicity (Inf. with) (non-poultry including wild birds)
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Summary
Report type: Immediate notification
Started: 5 Dec 2022
Confirmed: 12 Dec 2022
Reported: 15 Dec 2021
Reason for notification: Recurrence
Last occurrence: 23 Nov 2022
Causal agent: Highly pathogenic avian influenza virus
Serotype: H5N1
Nature of diagnosis: Clinical, laboratory
This event pertains to the whole country.

Outbreak location: Hong Kong Wetland Park, Yuen Long
Started: 5 Dec 2022
Ended: 5 Dec 2022
Epidemiological unit: Not applicable
Total animals affected:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Killed and disposed of / Slaughtered or killed for commercial use / Vaccinated
Black-faced spoonbill (wild) / - / 1 / 1 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: A dead black-faced spoonbill was collected on 5 Dec 2022 at a mudflat in the Hong Kong Wetland Park. The black-faced spoonbill is a winter visitor mainly found in the Deep Bay area.

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: Unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comments: An intensive avian influenza surveillance system is in place for all poultry farms, pet bird shops and wild birds in Hong Kong. The H5N1-infected bird was detected in the ongoing territory-wide surveillance program on wild birds. No spread of the disease was evident. Cleaning and disinfection have been stepped up at the venue where the dead bird was found. There are 2 poultry farms located within 3 kilometers (1.86 mi) of where the bird was found. The Government had immediately informed the farms, and no abnormal mortality or symptoms of avian influenza among the chicken flocks were noted. The Government will closely monitor poultry farms and the wholesale market to ensure that proper precautions against avian influenza have been taken. The government will continue its wild bird monitoring and surveillance.

Control measures at event level
Wild control measures applied: Screening, disinfection

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Centre of Influenza Research, School of Public Health, Li Ka Shing Faculty of Medicine, University of Hong Kong / Black-faced spoonbill / Virus isolation / 12 Dec 2022 / Positive
Centre of Influenza Research, School of Public Health, Li Ka Shing Faculty of Medicine, University of Hong Kong / Black-faced spoonbill / Gene sequencing / 9 Dec 2022 / Positive
Tai Lung Veterinary Laboratory, Agriculture Fisheries and Conservation Department (national laboratory) / Black-faced spoonbill / Real-time reverse transcription-polymerase chain reaction (rRT-PCR) / 7 Dec 2022 / Positive
Tai Lung Veterinary Laboratory, Agriculture Fisheries and Conservation Department (national laboratory) / Black-faced spoonbill / Gene sequencing / 7 Dec 2022 / Positive
Tai Lung Veterinary Laboratory, Agriculture Fisheries and Conservation Department (national laboratory) / Black-faced spoonbill / Immunohistochemistry (IHC) / 7 Dec 2022 / Positive

[The location of the outbreak can be seen on the interactive map included in the WOAH report at the source URL above.

